<subdoc-abstract>
<paragraph id="A-0001" lvl="0">Described is a new Avocado variety whose fruit matures at a minimum of approximately 4 to 6 weeks earlier than the variety &lsquo;Hass&rsquo;. </paragraph>
</subdoc-abstract>
<subdoc-description>
<summary-of-invention>
<section>
<heading lvl="1">BACKGROUND OF THE INVENTION </heading>
<paragraph id="P-0001" lvl="0"><number>&lsqb;0001&rsqb;</number> Avocado plants in cultivation are mainly varieties of Persea Americano. The new variety was developed by open pollination followed by seedling selection: an open pollinated seedling was selected at applicant&apos;s property in Kwinana, Hope Valley, Western Australia. which displayed precocious and consistent fruit, and which was an improvement to the variety &lsquo;Hass&rsquo; inasmuch as it consistently matured earlier than &lsquo;Hass&rsquo;. DNA profiling has shown that &lsquo;Hass&rsquo; is likely to be one of the parents of the new variety. Propagation by vegetative grafting onto rootstocks in Kwinana, Hope Valley, Western Australia has demonstrated that the characteristics of the new variety are transmitted through succeeding generations of asexual reproduction. </paragraph>
</section>
<section>
<heading lvl="1">SUMMARY OF THE INVENTION </heading>
<paragraph id="P-0002" lvl="0"><number>&lsqb;0002&rsqb;</number> The present invention is a new and distinctive Avocado plant having precocious and consistent fruit set similar to that of its parent variety, &lsquo;Hass&rsquo;, but matures consistently approximately 4 to 6 weeks earlier than that of its parent variety &lsquo;Hass.&rsquo;</paragraph>
<paragraph id="P-0003" lvl="0"><number>&lsqb;0003&rsqb;</number> The new variety was asexually reproduced by vegetative grafting onto Guatemalan Avocado seedling rootstocks and then advantageously planted in soil consisting of deep sands. </paragraph>
</section>
</summary-of-invention>
